rent from Japanese. In the early 2000s, JSL really took off when the government started making efforts to proliferate JSL and increase the number of interpreters proficient in JSL. %0a%3c %0a%3c Aside from signing, JSL has three different modes of communication including Yubimoji (Finger Spelling), Kuusho (Air writing), and Kouwa (Mouthing). Yubimoji is the most similar to Japanese writing (namely Hiragana/Katakana), in which one character is roughly equal to one sound. It is generally used for foreign words, last names, or unknown words. Kuusho and Kouwa utilize Japanese Kanji, borrowed characters from Chinese character sets, where one character represents a whole word or idea.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: B:)%0a%3c (:Category: SignLanguage:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
